 less learned Irish response. Then he turns to Irish debates on nobility, medicine and theology in order to illuminate the problem of human heredity. He concludes by demonstrating how the Enlightenment swept away these humanist theories of body and society, prior to the development of modern racial ideology in the late eighteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanismzIrelandxHistoryy17th century. 0aRenaissancezIreland. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAristotelianism.  aEarly modern.  aEmpire.  aEnlightenment.  aEthnicity.  aIreland.  aRace.  aRenaissance Humanism.1 aCampbell, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610264540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102645/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles